				<div class="social-last-reply-when">Last reply was March 24, 2011</div><div class="cf-clearfix"></div>				<ol class="social-commentlist">
				<li class="wordpress even thread-even depth-1 social-comment social-clearfix social-wordpress" id="li-comment-279">
<div class="social-comment-inner social-clearfix" id="comment-279">
	<div class="social-comment-header">
		<div class="social-comment-author ">
			<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/1636cff0bdc048e44673277c54bd9764?s=40&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/1636cff0bdc048e44673277c54bd9764?s=80&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' /><cite class="social-fn fn">David Erickson</cite>		</div>
		<!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
		<div class="social-comment-meta social-comment-meta-wordpress">
			<span class="social-posted-from">
								<span>View</span>
							</span>
			<a href="http://werblog.com/2011/03/is-open-flow-neither-open-nor-flow-talk-among-yourselves/#comment-279" class="social-posted-when" target="_blank">March 24, 2011</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="social-comment-body">
				<p>Just as an FYI, it is entirely conceivable that everyone who runs an AS would have their own &#8216;centralized&#8217; OpenFlow controller, which as far as I can tell still satisfies the definition of &#8216;de-centralized intelligence&#8217;.  I&#8217;m not sure anyone as this point is arguing for a centralized controller for the entire internet.</p>
	</div>
			<div class="social-actions entry-meta">
			</div>
		<!-- .reply -->
</div><!-- #comment-279 -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
<li class="wordpress odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 social-comment social-clearfix social-wordpress" id="li-comment-280">
<div class="social-comment-inner social-clearfix" id="comment-280">
	<div class="social-comment-header">
		<div class="social-comment-author ">
			<img alt='' src='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/26171bcf3615054cfd19c02014dd9237?s=40&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/26171bcf3615054cfd19c02014dd9237?s=80&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' /><cite class="social-fn fn"><a href='http://hightechforum.org' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Richard Bennett</a></cite>		</div>
		<!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
		<div class="social-comment-meta social-comment-meta-wordpress">
			<span class="social-posted-from">
								<span>View</span>
							</span>
			<a href="http://werblog.com/2011/03/is-open-flow-neither-open-nor-flow-talk-among-yourselves/#comment-280" class="social-posted-when" target="_blank">March 24, 2011</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="social-comment-body">
				<p>Networks are neither fully centralized nor fully decentalized; they&#8217;re more like &#8220;multiply centralized&#8221; around switches and routers. Netheads have never really understood this, and as a result the Internet has never been any more decentralized than the global telephone network. In both cases, independent networks interoperate with other on their own terms.</p>
<p>The language for articulating what&#8217;s unique about the Internet has never been very accurate, in other words. </p>
<p>Open Flow is a virtual network underneath the Internet, which is a virtual network itself. From my POV, Open Flow is the first system to grasp the fact that the virtual network thing has been the essence of the Internet all along; all this end-to-end malarkey is just one blind man&#8217;s theory of the elephant.</p>
	</div>
